#NationalFoodStrategy
There needs to be better recognition that healthy foods need to be accessible to those families on low incomes in order to reduce health inequalities.
The BDA supports the recommendation to address the very real needs of those with low levels of food security and extend free school meals.
The BDA strongly supports the creation of a ¬£150million fund to create ‚ÄòWhat works centres‚Äô drawing on good practice and tested activities.
The BDA supports the principles of a Sugar and Salt Reformulation Tax as a dynamic tool with which to address market imbalances and supports sugar and salt reduction modifications for foods.
The ambitions of the National Food Strategy demand the application of dietetic evidence-based practice and behaviour change approaches.
We expect to see greater involvement of UK dietitians to ensure that dietetic expertise of working at the public interface is collaboratively incorporated into the strategy at a national level.

National Food Strategy: Our response has been guided by engagement with our senior team, Board
of Directors and the knowledge and expertise of BDA specialist groups. https://t.co/azYMpahK6d

Dietitians are perfectly placed to help navigate the complex messages surrounding this. They're able to translate guidance to help the public understand what practical changes can be made to improve both their own health and that of our planet.
We need to work together to combat climate change. By making dietary changes, it‚Äôs win-win for the planet and health if we all act now.

There is mounting pressure for radical change from leading environmental specialists, organisations, and governments - as well as growing public interest and
support.
In this, the early part of the 21st century, it is accepted that our eating habits are having an adverse impact on the environment and we are endangering the future of the planet.

The speck on the photo taken by Voyager 1 as it left our solar system, is Planet Earth. It sits on the western spiral arm of an unremarkable galaxy in an unremarkable part of space. But it is our home. The only one we have and taking care of it lies with us.

We don't recommend any one food over another, but instead encourage eating a variety of foods to maintain a healthy balanced diet.

There are many nutrients that are involved with the normal functioning of the immune system, so we would encourage maintaining a health balanced diet in order to support immune function (include copper, folate, iron, selenium, zinc and vitamins A, B6, B12, C and D).
